Dialogue: 0,0:01:09.23,0:01:11.07,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,在十分遥远的地方\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Far, far away...
Dialogue: 0,0:01:16.75,0:01:18.03,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,越过火星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..beyond Mars...
Dialogue: 0,0:01:20.63,0:01:24.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,穿过木星的风暴和土星环\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..past the storms of Jupiter, and the rings of Saturn...
Dialogue: 0,0:01:26.67,0:01:28.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,太空中的环境变得截然不同\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..conditions become very different.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:31.83,0:01:36.63,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这里的温度骤降 不同行星之间的距离\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Temperatures plummet, and distances between worlds
Dialogue: 0,0:01:36.63,0:01:40.67,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,不再是数千万公里 而是以数十亿公里来计算\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} are measured not in millions, but in billions of kilometres.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:43.23,0:01:46.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,太阳系所有行星中最神秘的一颗就在这里\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Here lie the most mysterious planets of them all.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:51.35,0:01:52.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,天王星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Uranus.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:54.47,0:01:57.67,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,一颗有着大理石纹理的淡蓝色星球\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} A pale blue marble hanging in the dark,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:57.67,0:01:59.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,悬在黑暗冰冷的太空深处\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} frozen depths of space.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:03.39,0:02:05.31,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,在更加遥远的地方\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And, further out...
Dialogue: 0,0:02:06.47,0:02:09.19,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,则是太阳系最后一颗真正的行星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..the solar system's final true planet...
Dialogue: 0,0:02:12.39,0:02:14.27,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,海王星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..Neptune.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:16.99,0:02:21.47,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,再往远处去 人们一度以为 那里只有体积很小 死气沉沉\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Beyond, we thought we'd only ever find tiny, lifeless worlds...
Dialogue: 0,0:02:22.99,0:02:24.35,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,内核完全冰冻的天体\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..frozen to the core.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:28.79,0:02:30.79,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,但我们完全错了\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} How wrong we were.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:32.87,0:02:42.43,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,黑暗之地\N太阳系外缘
Dialogue: 0,0:02:57.23,0:03:00.67,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,在我们生活的这个时代 人类文明触及到了前所未有的空间范围\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} We live at a time when our civilisation has unprecedented
Dialogue: 0,0:03:00.67,0:03:04.31,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我们对火星保持了几乎长久性的探测\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} reach, and we have a near-permanent presence at Mars,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:04.31,0:03:08.55,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,包括火星轨道和火星表面 我们发射的探测器\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} both in orbit and on the surface, and we've had spacecraft orbiting
Dialogue: 0,0:03:08.55,0:03:13.99,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,已能环绕水星 金星 木星和土星完成长时间运行\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Mercury, Venus, Jupiter and Saturn for extended periods.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:13.99,0:03:18.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,但若要超出土星的距离 空间探测就变得困难许多\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} But, once we get beyond Saturn, things become much more difficult.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:18.39,0:03:20.91,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,到达那里的距离极其遥远\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} The distances are vast.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:20.91,0:03:23.15,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,飞行时间不是几个月\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Travel times are measured not in one months,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:23.15,0:03:27.35,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,而是几年甚至几十年 我们一次只能探访\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} but in years, decades, even. And that means that we've only
Dialogue: 0,0:03:27.35,0:03:30.23,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,一颗太阳系外层的行星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} visited the outer planets once.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:31.91,0:03:36.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,每一次造访都是进入未知世界的远行\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Each visit is a voyage into the unknown, as we strive
Dialogue: 0,0:03:36.75,0:03:40.63,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,因为我们要前往人类所探索的最遥远的行星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} to reach the most distant planetary systems ever visited.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:42.91,0:03:46.67,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,当我们到达那里时 探测器的速度太快了\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And, when we do get there, our spacecraft are travelling so fast
Dialogue: 0,0:03:46.67,0:03:49.15,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,以至于它们只能径直飞过\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} that they fly straight through,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:49.15,0:03:52.19,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,仅在行星范围内停留数小时\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} only spending a few hours in the system.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:52.19,0:03:57.27,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,不过这几个小时里收集的数据\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} But those few hours of precious data have allowed us to begin
Dialogue: 0,0:03:57.27,0:04:01.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,让我们得以开始了解那些隐藏在太阳系\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} to understand the mysteries that lie there on the outer edges
Dialogue: 0,0:04:01.39,0:04:02.83,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,边缘空间的秘密\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} of the solar system.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:04.63,0:04:11.23,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,“旅行者”2号探测器 1977年
Dialogue: 0,0:04:06.03,0:04:09.19,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,点火完毕 发射完毕\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} We have ignition and we have liftoff.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:14.99,0:04:21.59,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,用以探测太阳系外层空间
Dialogue: 0,0:04:21.07,0:04:24.23,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,返回的报告表明两台固体发动机\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Reports coming back indicate those twin, large, solid motors
Dialogue: 0,0:04:24.23,0:04:26.11,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,运转完全正常\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} are functioning perfectly.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:31.11,0:04:34.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,人类第一次飞向黑暗之地的任务能够完成 全都要归功于\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Our first mission into the dark was only possible thanks to some
Dialogue: 0,0:04:34.75,0:04:37.11,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这些行星自身提供的帮助\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} help from the planets themselves.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:43.63,0:04:46.51,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,每个行星的公转速度都是不同的\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Each planet orbits at a different speed.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:49.51,0:04:52.83,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,大部分时间里它们会分散在太阳的周围\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And, for most of the time, they're scattered around the Sun.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:58.75,0:05:02.27,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,但每隔175年\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} But once every 175 years...
Dialogue: 0,0:05:04.79,0:05:06.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,就会出现一个相当奇妙的现象\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..something rather wonderful happens.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:10.55,0:05:12.47,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,太阳系外层的这几颗行星会排成一条线\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} The outer planets align...
Dialogue: 0,0:05:14.35,0:05:15.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这就打开了一条\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..creating a path...
Dialogue: 0,0:05:17.35,0:05:20.79,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,从地球出发 途经木星和土星的通道\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..that leads from Earth past Jupiter and Saturn...
Dialogue: 0,0:05:24.79,0:05:27.63,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,并且能一直通向天王星和海王星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..all the way to Uranus and Neptune.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:45.27,0:05:50.23,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,“旅行者”2号正好赶在这个恰当的时机发射\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Voyager 2 had been launched at precisely the right moment
Dialogue: 0,0:05:50.23,0:05:53.55,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,以利用这一罕见的行星连珠现象\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} to take advantage of this rare planetary alignment.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:03.47,0:06:07.07,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它用了不到两年的时间到达木星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} It arrived at Jupiter in a little under two years.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:10.99,0:06:12.99,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,木星的质量是其它七大行星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Two and a half times more massive
Dialogue: 0,0:06:12.99,0:06:15.51,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,质量总和的2.5倍还多\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} than all the other planets combined...
Dialogue: 0,0:06:17.19,0:06:20.51,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,“旅行者”2号利用木星的引力把自己弹了出去\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..Jupiter gave Voyager a gravitational kick.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:31.71,0:06:34.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,又过了两年 “旅行者”2号见证了\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Another two years on, and Voyager witnessed
Dialogue: 0,0:06:34.39,0:06:37.59,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,太阳系中最美丽的景象之一\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} one of the most beautiful sights in the solar system.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:40.87,0:06:43.35,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,另一个气态巨行星的冰环\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} The icy rings of another gas giant...
Dialogue: 0,0:06:45.95,0:06:47.55,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这就是土星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..Saturn.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:01.31,0:07:03.67,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,然后探测器继续前进\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And, then, on and on...
Dialogue: 0,0:07:07.19,0:07:09.11,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,深入黑暗世界\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..further into the darkness.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:27.31,0:07:31.83,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,在离开地球将近9年后 “旅行者”2号逐渐靠近了\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Almost nine years after leaving Earth, Voyager approached
Dialogue: 0,0:07:31.83,0:07:34.15,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,一个全新类型的行星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} an entirely new class of planet.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:38.50,0:07:43.98,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,天王星 距离太阳29亿公里
Dialogue: 0,0:07:45.51,0:07:49.47,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,与木星和土星一样 天王星表面主要是\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Just like Jupiter and Saturn, the planet's upper atmosphere
Dialogue: 0,0:07:49.47,0:07:53.43,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,氢气和氦气形成的旋涡流\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} is composed mostly of swirling hydrogen and helium gas.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:00.99,0:08:05.31,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,在表面之下隐藏的是罕见的冰状混合物 含有甲烷\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And hidden beneath lies an exotic, icy mix of methane,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:05.31,0:08:06.95,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,氨和水\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ammonia and water.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:17.35,0:08:22.27,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,但与气态巨行星不同的是 天王星几乎没什么明显的动态特征\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} But, unlike the other gas giants, Uranus is almost featureless.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:26.39,0:08:29.03,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,“旅行者”2号在整个观测过程中\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} For all the time that Voyager stared at the planet,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:29.03,0:08:32.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,只看到了10个云层\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} it saw just ten cloud formations.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:35.51,0:08:37.35,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,人们很快发现了其中的原因\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And we soon discovered why.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:43.15,0:08:47.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,天王星只有零下224摄氏度\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Uranus, at -224 degrees Celsius,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:47.75,0:08:50.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,是太阳系最冷的行星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} is the coldest planet in the solar system.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:51.71,0:08:54.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,也是第一颗被发现的冰巨星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} The first of the ice giants,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:54.39,0:08:57.91,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它处于永久性深度冻结状态\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} in a permanent state of deep freeze.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:06.67,0:09:09.43,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,“旅行者”2号在天王星附近只逗留了6个小时\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Voyager spent just six hours with Uranus...
Dialogue: 0,0:09:11.23,0:09:15.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,随着视野扩大 它看清了整个天王星系统\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..and, as its gaze widened, it took in the entire system.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:27.03,0:09:28.63,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,和土星一样\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Just like Saturn...
Dialogue: 0,0:09:29.67,0:09:32.31,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,天王星也有行星环\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..Uranus has rings.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:52.47,0:09:55.55,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它的行星环十分微弱 暗淡 很难从地球上\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} The rings are so dark, so faint, that they're very difficult
Dialogue: 0,0:09:55.55,0:09:57.27,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,观察到\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} to see from Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:57.27,0:10:00.43,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,事实上 人们直到1977年才发现它们\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} In fact, we didn't discover them until 1977.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:01.47,0:10:04.59,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这些行星环一定是由某种不易反射太阳光的物质组成的\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} They must be made of some kind of material that doesn't reflect
Dialogue: 0,0:10:04.59,0:10:07.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,但人们不知道那是什么\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} a lot of sunlight back, and we don't know what that is.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:07.71,0:10:10.63,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,一定不是像土星环那样的水冰\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} It can't be water ice like the rings of Saturn,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:10.63,0:10:12.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,不然它们的亮度会更亮\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} because they would be much brighter.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:12.75,0:10:16.59,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这些光环极脆 极薄\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} They're also extremely delicate and thin,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:16.59,0:10:20.11,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,而且十分令人不解的是 我们本以为环内的微粒\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and, again, that's a great mystery, cos you'd expect the particles
Dialogue: 0,0:10:20.11,0:10:24.11,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,会发生碰撞 行星环会随着时间推移而延展\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} to collide and the rings to spread out over time.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:24.11,0:10:25.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,但这种情况并未发生\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} That doesn't happen.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:35.27,0:10:38.11,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,所以这些光环一定是被什么东西固定住了\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} So, something must be holding those rings in place,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:38.11,0:10:41.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,“旅行者”2号拍到的这张照片\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and the answer can be seen in this photograph
Dialogue: 0,0:10:41.75,0:10:43.35,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,可以给出答案\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} taken by Voyager 2.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:43.35,0:10:48.95,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,可以看到一个很细的光环 它叫ε环\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} You can see a bright, thin ring, which is known as the epsilon ring,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:48.95,0:10:52.23,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,在它上面和下面可以看到两颗卫星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and, above it and below it, you can see two moons.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:52.23,0:10:56.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,里面那颗是天卫六 外面那颗是天卫七\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} The inner one is called Cordelia, and the outer one is called Ophelia.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:56.75,0:11:00.23,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,现在我们需要了解一下运行的轨道\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Now, the thing you need to know about orbits, a moon or a ring
Dialogue: 0,0:11:00.23,0:11:04.51,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,运行轨道离行星近的卫星或行星环粒子\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} particle that's orbiting closer to a planet is moving more slowly
Dialogue: 0,0:11:04.51,0:11:08.31,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,要比轨道远离行星的卫星或行星环粒子移动速度慢\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} than a moon or ring particle that's orbiting further away.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:08.31,0:11:11.55,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,所以如果ε环内的粒子\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And, so, if there's a particle in the epsilon ring that maybe
Dialogue: 0,0:11:11.55,0:11:14.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,发生碰撞损失能量后 开始往下落\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} has a collision, loses a bit of energy and starts to drop down,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:14.75,0:11:20.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,天卫六就会帮助粒子加速 重新回到环内\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} then Cordelia tends to accelerate that particle back up into the ring
Dialogue: 0,0:11:20.75,0:11:23.91,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,在引力作用下 使它加速\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} again to speed it up by its gravitational influence.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:23.91,0:11:27.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,反过来如果ε环外部边缘的粒子\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Whereas, if it's a particle on the outer edge of the epsilon ring,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:27.71,0:11:31.67,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,获得了更多能量 并开始上升\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} it gets a bit more energy and raises up in altitude,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:31.67,0:11:33.99,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,那么天卫七就会让它减速\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} then Ophelia tends to slow it down,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:33.99,0:11:36.79,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,并重新回到光环里\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and, so, it falls back into the ring again.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:36.79,0:11:40.51,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,通过这种机制 这些卫星保证了行星环\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And, by that mechanism, these moons keep the ring nice
Dialogue: 0,0:11:40.51,0:11:43.99,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,完整有序地环绕在天王星周围 也正是这个原因\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and neat around Uranus, and, for that reason,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:43.99,0:11:46.91,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它们又被称为牧羊卫星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} these moons have become known as shepherd moons.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:57.43,0:12:00.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,目前我们还未发现更多的牧羊卫星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Now, we haven't discovered any more shepherd moons.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:00.39,0:12:02.55,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,要知道“旅行者”2号只在天王星系统待了几个小时\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Voyager was only in the system for a few hours.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:04.95,0:12:08.63,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,不过我们认为还存在更多 它们环绕天王星运转\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} But we assume that they're there, orbiting around Uranus,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:08.63,0:12:11.31,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,确保其它的行星环各归其位\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} keeping the other rings precisely in place.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:16.95,0:12:21.03,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,消失的卫星并非天王星唯一让人疑惑不解的谜团\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} The missing moons are not the only mysterious thing about the planet.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:27.19,0:12:30.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这颗行星以独一无二的方式环绕太阳运转\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Uranus orbits the Sun in a unique way,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:30.75,0:12:35.11,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这是很久以前发生的一系列事件导致的结果\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} a consequence of events that happened long ago.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:49.40,0:12:57.04,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,46亿年前
Dialogue: 0,0:12:58.11,0:13:01.07,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,天王星诞生于年轻太阳周围\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Uranus was born from the vast cloud of material
Dialogue: 0,0:13:01.07,0:13:03.11,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,巨大的团状物质之中\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} that surrounded the young Sun.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:05.03,0:13:07.47,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,久而久之 这团物质\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Over time, this material grew together
Dialogue: 0,0:13:07.47,0:13:09.63,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,在引力作用下聚集到一起\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} under the influence of gravity...
Dialogue: 0,0:13:13.47,0:13:15.23,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,每颗行星都是这样形成的\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..forming each of the planets...
Dialogue: 0,0:13:24.31,0:13:29.07,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,所有这些原始的气体尘埃云\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..all orbiting in the same anticlockwise direction
Dialogue: 0,0:13:29.07,0:13:31.91,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,都以逆时针方向旋转\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} as the primordial cloud of gas and dust.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:37.79,0:13:40.67,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这样的自转一直持续至今\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} This rotation remains to this day.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:43.99,0:13:46.91,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,几乎所有的行星都是沿自转轴\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Almost all the planets spin on their axis in the same
Dialogue: 0,0:13:46.91,0:13:48.83,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,以逆时针方向旋转\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} anticlockwise direction.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:52.59,0:13:55.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,但出于一些我们尚未完全理解的原因\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} But, for reasons we don't yet fully understand,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:55.75,0:14:00.51,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,金星和天王星都是以反方自转的\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Venus and Uranus spin on their axes in the opposite direction.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:08.03,0:14:10.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,天王星更是让人感到好奇\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And Uranus is even more curious.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:15.51,0:14:18.67,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,整颗星球都倒向一侧\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} The entire planet is on its side.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:28.35,0:14:32.67,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我们尚不确切了解为什么天王星以这种方式自转\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} It's not known for certain why Uranus spins in this way.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:32.67,0:14:35.11,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,不过有可能是在\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} But it seems likely that, at some point,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:35.11,0:14:39.47,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,遥远过去的某个时刻 它被另一个地球大小\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} probably in the distant past, it was hit by another planet,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:39.47,0:14:42.27,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,甚至更大的行星撞了一下\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} possibly the size of Earth or even larger,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:42.27,0:14:45.67,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,把它给撞倒了 而现代计算机\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} which knocked the planet over, and, indeed, modern computer
Dialogue: 0,0:14:45.67,0:14:48.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,模拟结果也显示 如果行星本身发生这种情况\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} simulations suggest that when you do that to a planet,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:48.75,0:14:52.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它所有的卫星也会随之变化 最终这个行星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} all the moons follow, and you end up with the planet
Dialogue: 0,0:14:52.71,0:14:56.27,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,和它的卫星系统 甚至包括它的行星环\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and its system of moons, and now its rings,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:56.27,0:14:59.91,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,都是横躺着沿螺旋线环绕太阳运转的\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} sort of corkscrewing around the Sun on its side.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:45.91,0:15:50.87,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,“旅行者”2号到达了人类探访过的距离最遥远的行星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Voyager had taken us to the most distant planets we had ever visited.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:59.27,0:16:06.15,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,而现在 这台空间探测器和它将邂逅的下一个天体之间\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And, now, an almost unthinkable distance of 1.6 billion kilometres
Dialogue: 0,0:16:06.15,0:16:11.15,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,相隔着几乎难以想象的 距离达16亿公里的\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} of icy cold space lay between the spacecraft
Dialogue: 0,0:16:11.15,0:16:12.83,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,冰冷宇宙空间\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and its next encounter.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:35.83,0:16:39.19,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,太阳系的规模之大是无法想象的\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} The size and scale of the solar system is impossible to imagine.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:41.03,0:16:45.79,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,但如果把所有东西按比例缩小 就变得比较形象了\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} But, when we scale everything down, then it becomes easier to visualise.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:45.79,0:16:50.55,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,太阳直径140万公里\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} The Sun is 1.4 million kilometres in diameter.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:50.55,0:16:54.87,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,但如果用它的直径除以6亿\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} But scale that down by a factor of around 600 million,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:54.87,0:16:58.43,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它大概就是那盏灯那么大了\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and it becomes the size of that light.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:58.43,0:17:01.91,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,那么地球 火星和其它岩质行星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And the Earth, Mars and the rocky planets
Dialogue: 0,0:17:01.91,0:17:05.19,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,按比例来说大约只有这么大\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} are about that big on this scale.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:05.19,0:17:09.95,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它们之间的距离则更加令人惊叹\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And the distances are, I think, even more remarkable.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:09.95,0:17:12.95,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,离太阳最近的水星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} So, Mercury, the closest planet to the Sun,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:12.95,0:17:15.43,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,就要一直往那边去 直到海边\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} would be all the way over there by the sea.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:24.57,0:17:34.01,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,水星
Dialogue: 0,0:17:25.23,0:17:28.67,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这里就是水星的轨道\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} So, this would be where Mercury orbits.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:28.67,0:17:32.55,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,相当于水星距离太阳96米\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And Mercury is 96 metres away.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:33.59,0:17:37.59,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它的直径还不到一厘米\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} It's about just under a centimetre in diameter.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:37.59,0:17:40.87,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,下一个行星金星就在那边\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And the next planet, Venus, is somewhere over there.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:41.81,0:17:50.41,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,水星                         金星
Dialogue: 0,0:17:45.39,0:17:50.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,从太阳出发飞行大约180米会经过金星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} We'd fly past Venus about 180 metres away from the Sun.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:54.35,0:17:58.51,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,然后继续向远处的地球进发\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And then head onwards and outwards towards the Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:05.47,0:18:09.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,在地球的轨道这里 我们可以切身体会到\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Here, at the Earth's orbit, the true scale of our fragility
Dialogue: 0,0:18:06.17,0:18:14.73,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,地球
Dialogue: 0,0:18:09.71,0:18:11.95,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,人类是多么脆弱 多么孤独\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and isolation becomes apparent.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:14.67,0:18:19.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,太阳在那里 有250米远 后面是遥远银河系\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} The Sun there, 250 metres away with the twinkling stars
Dialogue: 0,0:18:19.75,0:18:23.59,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,闪烁的星星 地球的直径\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} of the galaxy beyond, and here's the Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:23.59,0:18:26.35,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,是两厘米\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Two centimetres across.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:26.35,0:18:30.07,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,人类的全部历史就在这卵石大小的地方上演\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} On that pebble, all of human history play out.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:39.07,0:18:42.27,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,在大约380米处我们经过了火星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} At around 380 metres, we pass by Mars,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:42.27,0:18:46.51,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这是最后一个岩质行星 然后继续深入黑暗空间\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} the last of the rocky planets, and then onwards into the darkness.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:55.69,0:19:09.01,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,水星  金星  地球  火星
Dialogue: 0,0:19:10.07,0:19:13.11,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,渡过海湾 我们将到达\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Crossing the harbour takes us to the fringes
Dialogue: 0,0:19:13.11,0:19:14.55,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,外太阳系的边缘地带\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} of the outer solar system.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:17.83,0:19:20.19,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,行星之间的距离和行星的体积\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And, now, the distances and the sizes
Dialogue: 0,0:19:19.17,0:19:24.49,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,水星 金星 地球 火星
Dialogue: 0,0:19:20.19,0:19:22.27,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,变得越来越大\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} are beginning to get really big.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:26.31,0:19:29.15,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,木星是太阳系最大的行星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Jupiter, the largest planet in the solar system,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:29.15,0:19:35.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,直径是地球的10倍还多 太阳在那里\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} is over ten times the diameter of our Earth, and there's the Sun,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:33.68,0:19:41.60,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,木星
Dialogue: 0,0:19:35.75,0:19:38.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,横跨海湾1.3公里\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} 1.3km across the harbour.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:58.51,0:20:01.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,走过几乎两倍于太阳到木星的距离之后\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} At almost twice the distance from the Sun to Jupiter,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:01.71,0:20:02.99,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我们到达了土星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} we reach Saturn.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:04.16,0:20:09.88,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,土星                              木星
Dialogue: 0,0:20:04.75,0:20:07.91,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,在这个比例下是2.4公里\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} 2.4km on our scale.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:09.79,0:20:13.19,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,接下来我们要真正进入太阳系的昏暗地带了\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And we really are now entering the twilight of the solar system.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:13.19,0:20:18.07,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这里的亮度和地球的清晨或傍晚时分差不多\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Light levels are like early morning or late evening here on Earth,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:18.07,0:20:20.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,不过我们还是能够看到夜空中的土星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} but we can still see Saturn in the night sky,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:20.71,0:20:24.19,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,因为这颗行星和它的行星环高度反光\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} because the planet and its rings are highly reflective.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:30.79,0:20:35.79,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,经过了所有岩质行星 经过了木星和土星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} As far again as all the rocky planets, and Jupiter and Saturn,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:35.79,0:20:37.35,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我们到达了天王星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} we reach Uranus.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:36.48,0:20:44.02,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,天王星
Dialogue: 0,0:20:43.59,0:20:48.31,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,要远离太阳30亿公里 我们开始充分体会到\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} 3 billion kilometres from the Sun, and we begin to fully appreciate
Dialogue: 0,0:20:48.31,0:20:50.27,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,“旅行者”2号究竟走了多么远\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} the distances Voyager had travelled...
Dialogue: 0,0:20:55.79,0:20:58.87,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这是一趟到达太阳系最远端的旅程\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..on its journey to the farthest reaches of the solar system.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:14.47,0:21:18.59,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,旅程的终点是海王星 一个直径大约\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Journey's end, Neptune, a ball of gas about
Dialogue: 0,0:21:18.59,0:21:21.23,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,7.5厘米的气态星球\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} 7.5 centimetres across.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:21.23,0:21:25.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,在我们这个比例下它距离太阳7.4公里\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} 7.4km away from the Sun on this scale.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:24.72,0:21:33.68,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,海王星
Dialogue: 0,0:21:32.47,0:21:37.31,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我们依然还在这个岛上 在雷克雅未克的海湾\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And we are still down there on the island in Reykjavik harbour.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:38.39,0:21:43.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,小到肉眼看不见的蚂蚁在这颗卵石表面上爬来爬去\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Little, microscopic ants crawling around on the surface of a pebble.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:08.63,0:22:12.95,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,尽管用了12年之久 “旅行者”2号最终还是\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} It had taken 12 years, but Voyager had finally crossed
Dialogue: 0,0:22:12.95,0:22:16.59,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,还是成功跨越了从地球到最遥远行星系统之间的\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} the great expanse of space between Earth and the most
Dialogue: 0,0:22:16.59,0:22:18.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,广阔宇宙空间\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} distant planetary system.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:27.96,0:22:33.20,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,海王星 距离太阳45亿公里
Dialogue: 0,0:22:33.47,0:22:34.51,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,海王星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Neptune.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:38.27,0:22:43.87,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,其质量是地球的17倍 甚至超过了天王星的质量\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} 17 times the mass of the Earth, and even more massive than Uranus.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:02.03,0:23:06.51,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,不过与它的姐妹行星形成对比的是 海王星的大气层\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} But, in contrast to its sister planet, Neptune's atmosphere
Dialogue: 0,0:23:06.51,0:23:08.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,有着猛烈的气象活动\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} is bursting with activity.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:22.43,0:23:26.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我们发现这是一颗存在极端天气的行星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} What we found was a planet of extreme weather,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:26.71,0:23:32.11,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,高空的大风让白色的甲烷云团翻涌而起 风速超过了\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} where high altitude winds whip white methane clouds around at speeds
Dialogue: 0,0:23:32.11,0:23:34.79,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,每小时2000公里\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} of over 2,000km/h.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:34.79,0:23:37.95,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这是整个太阳系风速最快的\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Those are the highest wind speeds anywhere in the solar system.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:44.52,0:23:54.20,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,南半球 大黑斑
Dialogue: 0,0:23:51.63,0:23:54.03,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,“旅行者”2号看到了一个大黑斑\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And Voyager saw a great, dark spot,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:54.03,0:23:56.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,跟木星的大红斑有些相似\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} not unlike Jupiter's great, red spot.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:58.95,0:24:03.19,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这个风暴系统有地球大小 但当我们在四五年后\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} A storm system the size of Earth, that, when we looked only four
Dialogue: 0,0:24:03.19,0:24:06.31,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,再观察时 发现它已经消失了\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} or five years later, we found had vanished.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:10.35,0:24:13.83,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,多年以来 我们在海王星上观察到了\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} But, over the years, we've observed more storms raging
Dialogue: 0,0:24:13.83,0:24:14.99,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,更多的风暴\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} over the planet.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:21.47,0:24:24.83,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这是行星探测领域的几大不解之谜之一\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} It's one of the great mysteries of planetary exploration,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:24.83,0:24:29.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,为什么一个行星距离太阳如此遥远\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} why a planet so far from the Sun, with so little energy falling
Dialogue: 0,0:24:29.75,0:24:33.51,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,大气层从太阳获得的能量如此之少 却会存在太阳系中\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} into its atmosphere from sunlight, can have the most extreme winds
Dialogue: 0,0:24:33.51,0:24:34.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,最猛烈的强风\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} in the solar system.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:36.27,0:24:39.47,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,“旅行者”2号还发现另一件令人困惑的事\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And Voyager made yet another puzzling discovery.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:39.88,0:24:47.28,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,平均气温 零下214摄氏度
Dialogue: 0,0:24:43.15,0:24:47.63,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,尽管距离太阳更远 海王星却比天王星温度要高\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Although further from the Sun, the planet is warmer than Uranus.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:52.19,0:24:54.99,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这些额外的能量来源至今仍是一个谜\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} The source of this extra heat remains a mystery.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:59.31,0:25:03.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,出于某种原因 海王星散发的热量\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} But, for some reason, Neptune emits over two and a half times
Dialogue: 0,0:25:03.39,0:25:05.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,是它从太阳接收热量的两倍半还多\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} the heat it receives from the Sun.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:09.87,0:25:14.51,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这种来自内部的热量或许解释了猛烈风暴的成因\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And this internal heat helps to explain the ferocious storms.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:18.43,0:25:21.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,在热量从行星核心一路向外散发到\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} As the heat makes its way from the core of the planet
Dialogue: 0,0:25:21.39,0:25:23.03,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,宇宙空间的过程中\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and out into space...
Dialogue: 0,0:25:27.47,0:25:29.67,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,整个大气层被搅动\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..it churns up the entire atmosphere...
Dialogue: 0,0:25:32.07,0:25:36.07,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,形成了不同于太阳系其它地方的大风\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..creating winds unlike anything seen elsewhere in the solar system.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:42.03,0:25:45.55,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,风速如此之快 很可能是因为\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} The probable reason that wind speeds can be so high
Dialogue: 0,0:25:45.55,0:25:49.31,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,像海王星这样的行星没有坚硬的表面\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} is because there's no solid surface on a planet like Neptune.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:49.31,0:25:53.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,各种奇怪液体在下面流淌 各种气体在上面飘\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} It's exotic liquids further down, and gases further up.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:53.71,0:25:55.91,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,但没有岩质的表面\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} But there's no rocky surface.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:55.91,0:26:00.47,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,那里没有高山和大陆来阻断\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} There are no mountains and continents to break up the flow
Dialogue: 0,0:26:00.47,0:26:04.47,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,大气中气体的流动 所以行星上的风暴\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} of atmospheric gases, and, so, the winds can just whip
Dialogue: 0,0:26:04.47,0:26:07.27,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,达到了超音速的速度\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} around the planet at supersonic speeds.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:24.51,0:26:28.91,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,“旅行者”2号在太阳系的这场宏大之旅就要结束了\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Voyager 2 had almost completed its grand tour of the solar system.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:45.43,0:26:47.79,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,不过它在进行孤独的\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} But before it began its lonely journey
Dialogue: 0,0:26:47.79,0:26:49.79,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,星际旅行之前\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} out into interstellar space...
Dialogue: 0,0:26:54.15,0:26:56.47,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,还有最后一个世界要探访\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..it had one, last world to visit.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:59.05,0:27:05.53,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,海卫一 海王星14颗卫星中最大的一颗
Dialogue: 0,0:27:06.67,0:27:12.11,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,海卫一 一颗巨大的卫星 表面覆盖着冻结的固态氮\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Triton, a vast moon covered in a sheen of frozen nitrogen.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:14.59,0:27:18.27,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我们本以为这个世界寂静无声\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} We expected it to be a silent, still world,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:18.27,0:27:21.91,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,但“旅行者”2号带来了最后一个惊喜\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} but Voyager was in for one, last surprise.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:56.47,0:27:59.43,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,当“旅行者”2号到达时\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} But, when Voyager arrived,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:59.43,0:28:03.59,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我们发现这个冰冻世界上存在地质活动\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} we saw geological activity on that frozen world.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:03.59,0:28:09.51,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我们看到喷涌向太空的间歇泉 高度达8公里\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} We saw geysers erupting up into space 8km high,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:09.51,0:28:14.11,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,裹挟着沿顺风方向 绵延100公里的深色物质\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and then carrying dark material 100km downwind.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:22.27,0:28:27.07,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,现在我们发现 理解喷发形成过程的关键在于\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Now, the key to understanding what process caused those eruptions
Dialogue: 0,0:28:27.07,0:28:31.11,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,喷发的间歇泉大都集中在海卫一表面\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} was that we noticed that the geysers tended to erupt on a place
Dialogue: 0,0:28:31.11,0:28:34.27,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,一个有微弱阳光照射的地方\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} on Triton's surface below the faint Sun,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:34.27,0:28:37.31,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,尽管太阳远在数十亿公里之外\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} even though it's so many billions of miles away.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:37.31,0:28:41.99,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这个过程中 阳光照射在一层薄薄的氮冰上\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} What's happening is the sunlight is falling on the thin layer
Dialogue: 0,0:28:41.99,0:28:47.27,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,穿透冰层 然后使一层深色的 位于地表之下一米的\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} of nitrogen ice, going through, and heating up a layer of darker
Dialogue: 0,0:28:47.27,0:28:49.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,物质温度变高\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} particles a metre below the surface.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:52.87,0:28:55.55,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,仅仅4摄氏度的温度\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} A difference of just four degrees Celsius
Dialogue: 0,0:28:55.55,0:28:58.91,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,就足以让热量向上升腾\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} is enough for the heat to radiate up
Dialogue: 0,0:28:58.91,0:29:03.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,使冻结的氮蒸发形成气体\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and vaporise the frozen nitrogen, creating gas.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:07.87,0:29:10.47,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,气体在压力下最终冲破了氮冰\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} That gas is under pressure, and, ultimately,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:10.47,0:29:12.79,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,裹挟着深色物质上升\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} it punches through the nitrogen ice
Dialogue: 0,0:29:12.79,0:29:17.31,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这也就形成了海卫一上面的间歇泉现象\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} carrying those dark particles up and making the geysers of Triton.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:22.47,0:29:25.15,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,在太阳系这个最偏僻的角落\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} In the furthest reaches of the solar system,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:25.15,0:29:29.15,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,阳光即便微弱 也足以产生力量 创造出这番\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} the faint light of the Sun is still enough to power the most
Dialogue: 0,0:29:29.15,0:29:31.31,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,距离最遥远的地质奇观\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} distant of geological wonders.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:36.15,0:29:40.47,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,不过这并不能完全解释海卫一的其它神秘特征\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} But this can't explain the rest of Triton's mysterious features.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:41.98,0:29:50.10,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,表面覆盖数千个裂缝和凹坑
Dialogue: 0,0:29:50.35,0:29:53.87,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,如此显著的地形特征 只可能是由\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Terrain on this scale could only be created
Dialogue: 0,0:29:53.87,0:29:56.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,一股更强大的力量创造的\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} by a much more powerful force.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:01.11,0:30:05.67,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,线索似乎藏在海卫一奇特的运行轨道中\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And a clue seems to be lurking in Triton's odd orbit.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:12.59,0:30:15.43,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,不同于太阳系所有其它大个卫星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Unlike every other large moon in the solar system,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:15.43,0:30:20.67,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,海卫一的公转方向与海王星的自转方向是相反的\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Triton orbits in the opposite direction to the spin of the planet.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:20.67,0:30:22.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这说明海卫一和海王星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And that means it's highly unlikely
Dialogue: 0,0:30:22.75,0:30:25.55,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,不太可能是同时形成的\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} that Triton and Neptune formed at the same time.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:25.55,0:30:29.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,如果行星和它的卫星形成于同一片塌缩的气体尘埃云\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} If you formed a planet and a moon out of the same collapsing cloud
Dialogue: 0,0:30:29.71,0:30:33.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它们的自转和公转方向往住是一样的\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} of gas and dust, then they tend to spin and orbit in the same
Dialogue: 0,0:30:33.75,0:30:37.03,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,与最初的尘埃云旋转方向相同\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} direction as the spin of the initial dust cloud,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:37.03,0:30:42.03,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,所以最有可能的解释是 海卫一是海王星系统的\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} so, the most likely explanation for that is that Triton is a visitor
Dialogue: 0,0:30:42.03,0:30:46.31,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,一个访客 不过没像“旅行者”2号一样再离开\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} to the Neptunian system, that, unlike Voyager, never left.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:51.38,0:30:56.14,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,太阳系外围
Dialogue: 0,0:30:56.51,0:31:00.23,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,一种理论认为 数十亿年前\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} One theory is that, billions of years ago,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:00.23,0:31:02.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,海卫一并不是一颗卫星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Triton was not a moon at all.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:07.79,0:31:11.47,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它成长于海王星之外的一个区域\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} It grew up in a region of space way beyond Neptune...
Dialogue: 0,0:31:15.23,0:31:17.03,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这就是柯伊伯带\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..the Kuiper belt.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:23.43,0:31:27.79,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,在这里 数万亿由水 氨和甲烷\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Here, trillions of frozen lumps of water, ammonia
Dialogue: 0,0:31:27.79,0:31:30.23,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,组成的冰体环绕着太阳\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and methane circle the Sun.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:34.03,0:31:37.91,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它们是太阳系形成时的冰残留物\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} The frozen leftovers from the formation of the solar system.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:46.79,0:31:50.43,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,或许海卫一后来来到了这个区域的内缘\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Perhaps Triton ended up on the inner edge of this region...
Dialogue: 0,0:31:57.27,0:31:59.15,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,然后由于足够靠近海王星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..and ventured close enough
Dialogue: 0,0:31:59.15,0:32:01.99,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,导致被引力捕获\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} to Neptune to be drawn in by its gravity...
Dialogue: 0,0:32:05.91,0:32:10.43,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,直到它最终被拉出柯伊伯带\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..until, eventually, it was plucked from the Kuiper belt,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:10.43,0:32:15.07,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,永远被困在了这个遥远蓝色行星的轨道里\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and forever trapped in orbit around the distant, blue planet.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:24.67,0:32:28.99,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,如今海卫一围绕海王星公转的轨道是一个十分规整的圆圈\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Today, Triton orbits in a nice, regular circle around Neptune,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:28.99,0:32:31.19,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,不过它的轨道最初并不是这样的\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} but it wouldn't have started out that way.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:31.19,0:32:33.51,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,海卫一刚刚被捕获时 它应该是掠过了海王星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} When it was first captured, it would have glanced
Dialogue: 0,0:32:33.51,0:32:37.23,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,然后沿一个椭圆形轨道运行\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} past the planet and ended up in a wide, elliptical orbit,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:37.23,0:32:41.15,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,有时候离海王星很远 有时候很近\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} sometimes being far away from the planet, and sometimes close.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:41.15,0:32:44.47,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这意味着在海卫一围绕海王星公转的过程中\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} That means that, as Triton orbited around Neptune,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:44.47,0:32:47.51,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,万有引力是不断变化的\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} the gravitational pull was constantly changing,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:47.51,0:32:51.15,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它一直拉拽 碾压海卫一 并通过摩擦\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and that stretches and squashes the moon, and heats up
Dialogue: 0,0:32:51.15,0:32:52.99,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,使其内部温度上升\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} the interior by friction.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:52.99,0:32:54.95,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这个过程叫作潮汐加热\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} It's a process called tidal heating.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:58.43,0:33:01.87,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,炽热的内部物质很可能通过海卫一外壳上的\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} The molten interior would have exploded up through cracks
Dialogue: 0,0:33:01.87,0:33:03.95,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,裂缝和断层喷发出来\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and faults in Triton's crust...
Dialogue: 0,0:33:05.55,0:33:08.59,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,形成了我们今天看到的凹凸不平的表面\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..creating the ragged surface we see today.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:10.67,0:33:13.15,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,现在剩下的就是一个冷却下来的卫星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And what you're left with is a cooling moon,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:13.15,0:33:17.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,公转轨道为圆形 方向与行星自转方向相反\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} orbiting in a circle the wrong way around the planet,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:17.71,0:33:21.35,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它过去的动荡不得而见\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} the dramas of its past hidden from view.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:21.35,0:33:25.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,保留下来的只有那些间歇泉 微弱的太阳光为它们提供能量\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} All that remains are the geysers, powered by the faint light
Dialogue: 0,0:33:25.39,0:33:30.03,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,在如今沉寂的海王星表面留下了一道道深色纹路\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} of the Sun, painting dark streaks across the now-quiescent surface.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:42.07,0:33:44.99,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,“旅行者”2号已经完成了它的使命\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Voyager had fulfilled its mission,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:44.99,0:33:48.59,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,现在它继续前进 准备飞出太阳系\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and now headed onwards, out of the solar system...
Dialogue: 0,0:33:51.35,0:33:54.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它将不会再遇到另一颗行星了\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..where it would never encounter another planet.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:05.15,0:34:08.95,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,不过在别处 另一个世界正等着我们到访\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} But, elsewhere, another world awaited our arrival...
Dialogue: 0,0:34:11.67,0:34:13.87,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,一个更加深入黑暗的世界\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..far out in the darkness.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:17.87,0:34:22.11,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我们已经点火并发射了美国国家航空航天局的“新视野”号探测器\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Mission... And lift off of Nasa's New Horizons spacecraft
Dialogue: 0,0:34:22.11,0:34:27.15,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它将在10年的漫长航行后 造访“行星”冥王星 然后继续前进\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} on a decade-long voyage to visit the planet Pluto and then beyond.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:29.41,0:34:35.84,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,“新视野”号 2006年
Dialogue: 0,0:34:41.17,0:34:44.69,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,迄今发射速度最快的探测器
Dialogue: 0,0:34:45.31,0:34:47.19,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,“新视野”号\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} The New Horizons spacecraft,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:47.19,0:34:50.03,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,踏上了前往太阳系最边缘的旅程\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} on its way to the very edge of our solar system.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:49.53,0:34:52.65,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,前往冥王星飞行时间 9.5年
Dialogue: 0,0:35:01.63,0:35:04.79,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,人类想要了解这个奇妙小世界的雄心能否实观\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Our ambition to learn more about a small,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:04.79,0:35:09.31,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,取决于“新视野”号能否成功完成航行\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} intriguing world depended on the success of New Horizons.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:16.83,0:35:20.35,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这个长度不到3米的小探测器\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} As the tiny probe, less than three metres in length,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:20.35,0:35:22.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,被送进了宇宙深渊\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} was sent out into the abyss...
Dialogue: 0,0:35:28.31,0:35:32.35,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它的大部分电子器件和所有非必要系统\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..most of its electronics and all nonessential systems
Dialogue: 0,0:35:32.35,0:35:34.43,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,都为了节约电力而关闭了\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} were shut down to save power.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:37.15,0:35:43.27,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它将在全长48亿公里的航程中 几乎一直处于休眠状态\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} It would hibernate for almost its entire 4.8 billion kilometre trek.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:53.43,0:35:56.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,就在“新视野”号持续飞向冥王星的同时\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Whilst New Horizons continued its voyage to Pluto,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:56.71,0:36:00.67,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,地球上发生了一场关于冥王星定义\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} a controversy arose here on Earth about the definition
Dialogue: 0,0:36:00.67,0:36:02.27,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,的争论\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} of Pluto itself.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:02.27,0:36:05.31,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我们过去一直都知道冥王星很小\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} See, we always knew that Pluto is small,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:05.31,0:36:09.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,比海王星的卫星海卫一还要小 但直到哈勃空间望远镜\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} smaller than Neptune's moon Triton, but it was discoveries made
Dialogue: 0,0:36:09.75,0:36:13.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,在冥王星附近有了新的发现之后\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} in the vicinity of Pluto by the Hubble Space Telescope
Dialogue: 0,0:36:13.71,0:36:17.03,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它的行星地位才真正受到了挑战\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} that really challenged its status as a planet.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:21.27,0:36:26.59,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,从地球上看 远在柯伊伯带内缘的冥王星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} From Earth, Pluto, far away on the inner edge of the Kuiper belt,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:26.59,0:36:29.99,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,由于距离过于遥远 即使用哈勃望远镜\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} is so distant that, even with Hubble, it appears
Dialogue: 0,0:36:29.99,0:36:32.47,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,也只能看到一个模糊的图像\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} as nothing more than a fuzzy image.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:35.75,0:36:37.95,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,但冥王星并不孤单\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} But Pluto was not alone.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:40.23,0:36:43.19,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我们开始探测到其它遥远的天体\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} We began to detect other distant objects.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:45.08,0:36:48.24,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,夸欧尔 发现于2002年
Dialogue: 0,0:36:48.24,0:36:50.76,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,塞德娜 发现于2003年
Dialogue: 0,0:36:50.76,0:36:53.68,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,妊神星 发现于2003年
Dialogue: 0,0:36:53.68,0:36:56.28,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,鸟神星 发现于2005年
Dialogue: 0,0:36:56.19,0:36:59.23,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,之后哈勃望远镜又发现了一个\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Then, Hubble discovered that another world
Dialogue: 0,0:36:59.23,0:37:01.47,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,几乎与冥王星同等大小的天体\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} is almost the same size as Pluto.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:01.32,0:37:05.84,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,阋神星 直径2326公里
Dialogue: 0,0:37:09.83,0:37:14.15,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这些新发现的天体 让人们不得不重新思考\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} The discovery of these new worlds has forced us to reconsider
Dialogue: 0,0:37:14.15,0:37:16.51,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,“行星”这个词的含义\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} what we mean by the word "planet".
Dialogue: 0,0:37:20.67,0:37:24.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,国际天文学联合会对行星的定义包括三点\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} The International Astronomical Union has a three-part definition
Dialogue: 0,0:37:24.75,0:37:27.51,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,第一 它必须围绕太阳公转\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} of a planet. Firstly, it has to orbit the Sun,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:27.51,0:37:29.47,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,冥王星确实如此\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and Pluto certainly does that.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:29.47,0:37:32.31,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它每248年公转一次\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} It goes round once every 248 years.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:32.31,0:37:37.23,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,第二 它必须质量足够大 好让它在引力作用下\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Secondly, it has to be massive enough for gravity to sculpt it
Dialogue: 0,0:37:37.23,0:37:42.11,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,变成近似球形的形状 而冥王星基本也是一个球形\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} almost into a sphere, and Pluto indeed is almost spherical.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:42.11,0:37:46.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,第二 它围绕太阳运行的轨道上不能有障碍物\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} But, thirdly, it has to clear its own orbit around the Sun,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:46.75,0:37:50.19,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这其实也是对质量的要求\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and that's essentially a mass constraint as well.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:50.19,0:37:54.15,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它必须有足够大的引力来清除\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} It has to have enough gravity to throw things out
Dialogue: 0,0:37:54.15,0:37:56.07,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,公转轨道上的天体\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} from its orbital path.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:56.07,0:37:58.59,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,而冥王星并不符合这样的要求\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And that's where Pluto falls down.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:58.59,0:38:01.47,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,那么为什么要加上这一条呢\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Now, why that extra idea?
Dialogue: 0,0:38:01.47,0:38:05.07,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,说到底这是因为 如果冥王星大到足够成为一颗行星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Well, ultimately, it's because if Pluto is big enough
Dialogue: 0,0:38:05.07,0:38:08.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,那么就体积而言阋神星也是行星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} to be a planet, then Eris is big enough to be a planet,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:08.39,0:38:11.23,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,鸟神星也是一样的情况\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and Makemake is big enough to be a planet,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:11.23,0:38:15.67,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,数十个 甚至数百个足够大的天体\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and tens or even potentially hundreds of objects out there
Dialogue: 0,0:38:15.67,0:38:17.87,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,都有可能成为行星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} are big enough to be planets.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:17.87,0:38:20.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,所以这个条件真的那么重要吗\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Now, does it really matter?
Dialogue: 0,0:38:20.75,0:38:22.67,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我并不这么认为\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Well, I don't think so.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:22.67,0:38:28.11,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,冥王星终究还是一个天体 因此我们应该去探索它\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Ultimately, Pluto is a world, and, therefore, we should explore it.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:38.66,0:38:40.46,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,准备 1 2
Dialogue: 0,0:38:42.03,0:38:46.19,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这正是我们在2015年7月采取的行动\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And, in July 2015, that's exactly what we did.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:48.18,0:38:49.82,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,准备 中心平台
Dialogue: 0,0:38:52.27,0:38:56.87,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,经过9年的飞行 “新视野”号被唤醒\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} After nine years of flight, New Horizons awoke.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:58.71,0:39:00.51,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,收到\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Copy that.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:00.51,0:39:03.15,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我们正与太空营进行遥感对接\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} We are locked by telemetry with the phase path.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:15.77,0:39:21.53,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,冥王星 距离太阳59亿公里
Dialogue: 0,0:39:36.47,0:39:42.11,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我们第一次瞥见人类探测过的最遥远的星球\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} We had our first glimpse of the most distant world ever visited.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:48.13,0:39:57.57,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,克苏鲁斑 3000公里宽的黑暗地带
Dialogue: 0,0:39:58.01,0:40:05.45,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,超过5000个撞击坑
Dialogue: 0,0:40:05.45,0:40:10.90,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,光晕状撞击坑 维加台地区域
Dialogue: 0,0:40:10.90,0:40:17.09,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,光晕状撞击坑 维加台地区域\N（最大的撞击坑 50公里宽）
Dialogue: 0,0:40:17.09,0:40:22.13,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,丹增山脉 最高峰高达6公里
Dialogue: 0,0:40:29.43,0:40:31.95,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,冥王星十分美丽\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Pluto is beautiful.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:31.95,0:40:35.87,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它完全不是一个冰冷的 毫无特色的星球\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And, far from being a frigid, featureless world,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:35.87,0:40:38.31,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,事实证明 一颗充满活力的行星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} it turns out that it has all the characteristics
Dialogue: 0,0:40:38.31,0:40:40.79,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,该有的特色它全部具备\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} of a dynamic, living planet.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:40.79,0:40:45.87,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,没错 它的表面很冷 大约零下230摄氏度\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And, yes, it is cold on the surface, about -230 degrees Celsius.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:45.87,0:40:49.15,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,行走其上 脚下是坚硬的氮冰\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} I'd be walking over solid nitrogen.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:49.15,0:40:51.99,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,而在哈勃空间望远镜\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} But the blotches that could be made out
Dialogue: 0,0:40:51.99,0:40:56.35,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,模糊的图像上显示为黑斑的区域\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} in the grainy Hubble Space Telescope images turned out to be
Dialogue: 0,0:40:56.35,0:41:00.19,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,其实是及其丰富多样的地质形态和结构\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} a tremendous variety of geological form and structure.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:06.31,0:41:10.19,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,不过到目前为止辨识度最高的特征是一个叫作\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} But by far the most recognisable feature is the region known
Dialogue: 0,0:41:10.19,0:41:11.51,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,汤博区的区域\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} as Tombaugh Regio,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:11.51,0:41:15.19,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它有一个更为人所熟悉的名字 冥王星之心\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} or to give it its more popular name, Pluto's Heart.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:15.67,0:41:21.67,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,汤博区 冥王星之心
Dialogue: 0,0:41:20.95,0:41:24.67,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这个心形靠西的一瓣叫作斯普特尼克平原\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} The western lobe of the heart is called Sputnik Planitia.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:30.43,0:41:35.31,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这个广阔的平原由富含氮 甲烷和一氧化碳的冰体构成\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} A giant plain of frozen nitrogen, methane and carbon monoxide...
Dialogue: 0,0:41:38.15,0:41:41.43,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,面积达100万平方公里\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..that stretches for a million square kilometres.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:46.15,0:41:50.23,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,平原的边缘是绵延的山脉\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And, at its edge, lies a range of mountains made of pure,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:50.23,0:41:53.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,由纯净的水冰组成\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} frozen water ice...
Dialogue: 0,0:41:53.39,0:41:57.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,高出平原6公里之多\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..that rise up to 6km above the plain.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:02.83,0:42:06.47,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,不过这个区域有个不同寻常的特点\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} But there's something very strange about the region,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:06.47,0:42:10.51,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,使它有别于这个矮行星其余所有地方\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} something that sets it apart from the rest of this dwarf planet.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:15.11,0:42:18.59,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,冥王星表面遍布撞击坑\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} The surface of Pluto is covered in craters, the scars
Dialogue: 0,0:42:18.59,0:42:21.59,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,是数十亿年前天体撞击留下的疤痕\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} of impacts that have taken place over many billions of years,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:21.59,0:42:23.79,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,就像月球的表面一样\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} just like the surface of our moon.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:23.79,0:42:29.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,但我们看到的斯普特尼克平原十分平坦\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Except, if you look on Sputnik Planitia, it is absolutely smooth.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:29.71,0:42:33.43,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,上面是完全没有撞击坑存在的 连一个也不存在\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} There are no craters there at all, not a single one.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:35.83,0:42:39.07,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,在宇宙空间中 没有撞击坑是很不可思议的\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} From space, the lack of craters is striking.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:40.59,0:42:44.19,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我们观察的距离越近 它的秘密就越发让人不解\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And, the closer you look, the stranger the mystery gets.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:53.51,0:42:57.87,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,“新视野”号传回的精细图像显示\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Detailed imagery beamed back by New Horizons revealed a network
Dialogue: 0,0:42:57.87,0:43:00.47,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,一大片六边形和五边形的结构\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} of hexagon and pentagon shapes...
Dialogue: 0,0:43:05.99,0:43:09.15,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,在氮冰表面纵横交错\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..that crisscross the frozen nitrogen surface.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:20.59,0:43:24.91,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,找到成因的一个线索就在这些图像里\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} A clue to what might be happening can be seen in these images.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:24.91,0:43:28.95,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这类地表形态在宇宙的其它地方也能找到\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Those kind of patterns are found elsewhere in nature.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:28.95,0:43:31.83,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,比如这个是在太阳表面\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Here, for example, on the surface of the Sun.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:33.79,0:43:37.47,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,或者这个 从下方被加热的液体物质\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Or here, in a liquid that's been heated from below.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:38.99,0:43:42.19,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这些图案是对流的典型特征\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} These patterns are characteristic of convection.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:42.19,0:43:45.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它要有一个热源让物质做上升运动\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} There's a heat source which is causing material to rise up,
Dialogue: 0,0:43:45.71,0:43:49.95,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,物质冷却后又会下降回来 对流的液体\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and then it cools and falls back again, and in those circulating
Dialogue: 0,0:43:49.95,0:43:53.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,不断循环往复之后 就会出现这样的图案\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} convection currents, you tend to get patterns like this.
Dialogue: 0,0:43:56.31,0:43:59.91,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,所以斯普特尼克平原下面可能是这种情况\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} So, what could be happening below the surface of Sputnik Planitia
Dialogue: 0,0:43:59.91,0:44:04.03,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,地下深处有一个热源 它不断融化氮冰\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} is that there is a heat source deep down which is melting the nitrogen
Dialogue: 0,0:44:04.03,0:44:08.23,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,导致它上升 冷却 然后下降\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ice and causing it to rise, cool and then fall again,
Dialogue: 0,0:44:08.23,0:44:12.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,那些对流的液体不断重塑着这一地区的面貌\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and those convection currents are constantly resurfacing the area.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:17.27,0:44:22.11,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,冥王星这样的小星球依然很活跃 这是个巨大的惊喜\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} That a small world like Pluto is still active was a huge surprise.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:26.35,0:44:28.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我们对此最合理的解释就是\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Our best theory of how this could be
Dialogue: 0,0:44:28.71,0:44:31.55,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,星球内部深处的某个地方\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} is that somewhere deep in its interior...
Dialogue: 0,0:44:33.67,0:44:38.03,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,一些放射性物质在它们衰变的过程中不断产生热量\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..there are radioactive elements that generate heat as they decay.
Dialogue: 0,0:44:42.35,0:44:46.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这股热量不断温暖着一个没有光照 呈半冰冻状态的海洋\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} This heat warms a sunless, half-frozen ocean of water
Dialogue: 0,0:44:46.71,0:44:51.03,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它已在冥王星地表之下存在了数十亿年之久\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} that has existed for billions of years beneath the surface of Pluto.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:02.23,0:45:05.19,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,来自斯普特尼克平原的证据表明\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Now, the evidence from Sputnik Planitia that there is still
Dialogue: 0,0:45:05.19,0:45:09.35,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,星球内部的热源依然存在 通过研究冥王星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} an internal heat source, and studies of other geological features
Dialogue: 0,0:45:09.35,0:45:12.87,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,其它的地质特征 一些科学家推测\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} on Pluto, have led some scientists to suggest that
Dialogue: 0,0:45:12.87,0:45:15.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,那个海洋可能还在原地\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} that ocean of water might still be there.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:20.75,0:45:22.63,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,一个相对较暖的海洋\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And the relatively warm ocean
Dialogue: 0,0:45:22.63,0:45:26.15,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,或许能解释为什么斯普特尼克平原没有撞击坑\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} could explain the lack of craters on Sputnik Planitia.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:30.31,0:45:35.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,在氮冰表面缓慢上升的过程中\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} The entire area is constantly being repaved as the nitrogen
Dialogue: 0,0:45:35.71,0:45:37.91,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,整个区域不断地被重塑\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} surface is slowly turned over.
Dialogue: 0,0:45:48.99,0:45:52.51,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,但是为什么这种地质活动只会在这里出现呢\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} But why all this activity here and nowhere else?
Dialogue: 0,0:45:56.71,0:46:00.15,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,也许冥王星之心所在的地方发生过猛烈撞击\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Perhaps Pluto's heart is the site of a huge impact...
Dialogue: 0,0:46:03.15,0:46:07.15,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,很久以前 它的表面被撞出了一个大洞\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..that, long ago, punched a large hole in the surface,
Dialogue: 0,0:46:07.15,0:46:10.07,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,几乎深及那片广阔的地下海洋\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} almost down to the vast ocean beneath.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:12.83,0:46:17.03,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这个洞渐渐地被并不坚硬的氮冰所填满\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} A hole that's slowly filled with soft nitrogen ice...
Dialogue: 0,0:46:19.43,0:46:23.47,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这个温暖海洋促使其上的氮冰缓慢翻腾\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..that now gently churns just above a warmer ocean.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:26.27,0:46:27.63,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,想象一下\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Imagine that.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:27.63,0:46:31.59,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,有一片海洋 距离太阳数十亿公里之遥\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} An ocean billions of miles away from the Sun,
Dialogue: 0,0:46:31.59,0:46:34.59,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,位于太阳系寒冷的边缘地带\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} on the frozen frontier of the solar system.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:34.59,0:46:37.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,在这个最令人惊讶的星球上\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} On this most surprising of worlds,
Dialogue: 0,0:46:37.39,0:46:40.35,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,也许仍然存在着大量的水\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} there may still be an ocean of water.
Dialogue: 0,0:46:50.31,0:46:55.03,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,“新视野”号与冥王星最亲密的邂逅只持续了数小时\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} New Horizons' closest encounter with Pluto lasted just hours...
Dialogue: 0,0:47:03.43,0:47:06.35,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这个过程中只有一个半球是可见的\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..during which only one hemisphere was visible...
Dialogue: 0,0:47:08.43,0:47:10.83,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它的另一面仍是一个谜\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..leaving the other side a mystery.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:29.83,0:47:33.03,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,冥王星给了我们最后一个惊喜\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Pluto held a final surprise.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:33.03,0:47:37.19,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,就在“新视野”号调转镜头 准备再看最后一眼时\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} As New Horizons turned its camera back for one, last look...
Dialogue: 0,0:47:40.99,0:47:44.51,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它拍到了冥王星大气层\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..it captured an image of Pluto's atmosphere,
Dialogue: 0,0:47:44.51,0:47:46.23,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,在黑暗中闪耀的图像\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} glowing in the dark.
Dialogue: 0,0:47:52.55,0:47:56.87,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,个薄薄的蓝色大气层 下面隐藏着一片汪洋\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} A thin, blue sky over a hidden ocean of water...
Dialogue: 0,0:47:58.27,0:48:01.55,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这个地方与地球的距离是48亿公里\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..4.8 billion kilometres from Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:28.75,0:48:30.35,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,人类取得的成就是巨大的\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} We've come a long way.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:32.35,0:48:35.43,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,通过仅仅半个世纪的空间探测\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} After just half a century of space exploration...
Dialogue: 0,0:48:37.39,0:48:40.27,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我们造访了太阳系的每一个行星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..we've reached every one of the planets in the solar system...
Dialogue: 0,0:48:45.07,0:48:47.03,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,并开始讲述关于它们的故事\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..and begun to tell their story.
Dialogue: 0,0:48:57.39,0:49:00.55,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我们所呈现的是永不停息的变化\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} What's emerging is a tale of never-ending change...
Dialogue: 0,0:49:02.91,0:49:04.87,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,扣人心弦的起源\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..of dramatic origins...
Dialogue: 0,0:49:09.15,0:49:10.63,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,充满希望的瞬间\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..moments of hope...
Dialogue: 0,0:49:16.31,0:49:17.99,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,还有逝去\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..and loss.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:31.15,0:49:34.55,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,8个岩质的 冰冻的以及气态的尘埃\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Where just eight motes of rock, ice and gas...
Dialogue: 0,0:49:36.15,0:49:39.03,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,以黑暗的宇宙空间为幕布\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..set against the dark backdrop of space...
Dialogue: 0,0:49:40.47,0:49:45.67,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它们齐心协力 至少在其中一个世界创造出了生命\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..have conspired together to produce life on at least one world.
Dialogue: 0,0:49:58.91,0:50:01.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,有些人会问 我们为什么要探索宇宙\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} "Why do we explore?" some people ask.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:01.75,0:50:05.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,难道我们不应该先处理好地球上的种种问题 然后再投入时间\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Shouldn't we deal with the problems here on Earth before committing time
Dialogue: 0,0:50:05.71,0:50:10.43,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,精力和资源 去探索那些星星吗\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and energy and resources to exploring the stars?
Dialogue: 0,0:50:10.43,0:50:14.67,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我认为把注意力完全放在地球 这个宇宙尘埃上\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Well, I think focusing entirely on our mote of dust
Dialogue: 0,0:50:14.67,0:50:17.59,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,是莫大的错误\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} would be a profound mistake.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:17.59,0:50:20.95,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,那将意味着我们人类决定蜷缩在\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} It would mean that we've taken the decision to sit huddled
Dialogue: 0,0:50:20.95,0:50:23.87,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,太阳系的一个小角落里\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} in a tiny corner of the solar system,
Dialogue: 0,0:50:23.87,0:50:25.27,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,对我们所做的事情迷惑不解\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} wondering what we're doing here.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:27.63,0:50:31.59,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,那将意味着我们人类决定为了\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} It would mean that we've taken the decision to fight amongst
Dialogue: 0,0:50:31.59,0:50:34.83,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,越来越珍贵的资源而相互斗争\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ourselves for ever-more-precious resources,
Dialogue: 0,0:50:34.83,0:50:38.79,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,把自己限制在一层薄薄的大气之下 一块渺小的岩石之上\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} confined below a thin shell of air on a small rock,
Dialogue: 0,0:50:38.79,0:50:42.63,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,而不是去探索那条由夜晚星光\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} rather than following the three-dimensional path marked out
Dialogue: 0,0:50:42.63,0:50:44.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,勾勒出的立体的路径\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} by the lights in the night.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:53.79,0:50:56.91,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我们住在一个充满奇迹的太阳系\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} We live in a solar system of wonders,
Dialogue: 0,0:50:56.91,0:51:01.11,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这里有风暴肆虐的行星 冰冻的卫星 还有各种地貌和景观\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} of planets of storms and moons of ice and landscapes and vistas
Dialogue: 0,0:51:01.11,0:51:04.91,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它们激发我们的想象力 丰富着我们的精神世界\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} that stir the imagination and enrich the soul,
Dialogue: 0,0:51:04.91,0:51:08.99,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,太阳系有着无尽的资源 无与伦比的美丽\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} a system of limitless resources, limitless beauty
Dialogue: 0,0:51:08.99,0:51:10.79,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,以及无限的潜力\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and limitless potential.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:13.03,0:51:16.55,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我们对太阳系的探索才刚刚起步\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} A system that we've only just begun to explore...
Dialogue: 0,0:51:19.43,0:51:23.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,而这趟旅程已经给了我们众多收获\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..in a journey that has already rewarded us with so much.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:41.93,0:51:46.89,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,《行星》幕后故事
Dialogue: 0,0:51:49.47,0:51:53.63,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,冥王星是美国国家航空航天局计划探测过的最遥远的星球\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Pluto was the most distant world that Nasa had ever planned to visit.
Dialogue: 0,0:51:54.79,0:51:58.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} 10 9 8 7\NTen, nine, eight, seven...
Dialogue: 0,0:51:58.71,0:52:02.47,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,“新视野”号的发射格外紧张刺激\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} The launch of New Horizons was incredibly dramatic.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:04.43,0:52:06.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,点火 升空\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Mission... And liftoff.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:06.75,0:52:09.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它升空的速度太快了\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And it just shoots up so fast.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:09.39,0:52:11.59,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,是地球上速度最快的一次发射\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} It's the fastest launch ever from Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:11.59,0:52:13.55,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,速度大约是每秒10英里\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} About ten miles per second.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:18.59,0:52:22.43,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,为了确保探测器能在宇宙中持续飞行10年之后\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} In order to ensure that it was going to last for the decade across space
Dialogue: 0,0:52:21.42,0:52:25.46,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,戴维-格林斯普恩博士 行星科学研究所
Dialogue: 0,0:52:22.43,0:52:25.15,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,还能正常工作 他们做了很多备份工作\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and actually work there, they built in a lot of redundancy.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:25.15,0:52:27.59,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,基本上所有东西都有备份 包括计算机\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} There were sort of two of everything, computers
Dialogue: 0,0:52:27.59,0:52:29.43,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,导航系统\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and the guidance systems,
Dialogue: 0,0:52:29.43,0:52:31.47,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,他们还想出了让它休眠的办法\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and they figured out how to hibernate.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:31.47,0:52:33.99,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它是第一个休眠的探测器\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} The first spacecraft that hibernated.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:35.75,0:52:38.95,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我们让探测器大部分时间在睡觉\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} To put the spacecraft largely to sleep let the spacecraft
Dialogue: 0,0:52:38.95,0:52:40.83,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,让它只是安静地漫游太空\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} just silently coast,
Dialogue: 0,0:52:40.83,0:52:44.47,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这样我们就能延长电子器件的寿命了\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} then we could extend the life of the electronics.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:46.51,0:52:49.11,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,此前没有一架探测器\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} No spacecraft mission had ever really used hibernation
Dialogue: 0,0:52:46.82,0:52:51.74,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,艾伦·斯特恩 “新视野”号首席研究员
Dialogue: 0,0:52:49.11,0:52:52.51,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,以连续休眠的方式飞越太阳系\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} as a day-to-day way to cross the solar system.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:55.27,0:52:56.91,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这架探测器在睡梦中\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} As the spacecraft slept,
Dialogue: 0,0:52:56.91,0:52:59.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,加速飞离地球 驶向了它的目的地\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} it sped away from Earth towards its destination...
Dialogue: 0,0:53:01.15,0:53:03.27,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,那是几乎在整个人类历史长河中\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..to a world that had lain hidden
Dialogue: 0,0:53:03.27,0:53:06.63,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,都淹没在群星中的一个星球\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} amongst the stars for almost all of human history.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:08.39,0:53:13.07,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,冥王星发现于1930年 一个来自堪萨斯州的\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} The discovery of Pluto was in 1930, when Clyde Tombaugh,
Dialogue: 0,0:53:09.78,0:53:14.62,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,哈尔·韦弗 “新视野”号项目科学家
Dialogue: 0,0:53:13.07,0:53:14.63,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,农场小伙克莱德·汤博\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} a Kansas farm boy,
Dialogue: 0,0:53:14.63,0:53:19.47,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,用亚利桑那州当地一座天文台的望远镜发现了它\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} was using the telescope at the Lowell Observatory in Arizona.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:19.47,0:53:21.11,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,每个晴朗的夜晚\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Every clear night,
Dialogue: 0,0:53:21.11,0:53:23.99,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,克来德都会到外面\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Clyde would go out and take images
Dialogue: 0,0:53:21.82,0:53:27.10,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,凯西·奥尔金 “新视野”号副首席研究员
Dialogue: 0,0:53:23.99,0:53:27.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,用带底片的相机拍摄夜空 然后在多云\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} of the sky on photographic plates, and when it was cloudy
Dialogue: 0,0:53:27.39,0:53:29.95,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,或者白天的时候 比较这些底片\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} or during the day, he would compare those plates.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:29.95,0:53:34.55,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,克莱德·汤博发现有个小光点\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And Clyde Tombaugh noticed that there was this little speck
Dialogue: 0,0:53:34.55,0:53:36.07,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,在群星中移动\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} moving across the stars.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:36.07,0:53:40.15,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,后来在1930年 克莱德·汤博发现了冥王星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And, then, in 1930, Clyde Tombaugh discovered Pluto.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:41.51,0:53:44.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,然而汤博没能亲眼近距离观察冥王星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} But Tombaugh would never see Pluto up close.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:46.95,0:53:51.47,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,他逝世于“新视野”号发射前9年\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} He died nine years before the launch of New Horizons,
Dialogue: 0,0:53:51.47,0:53:53.27,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,享年90岁\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} at the age of 90.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:54.43,0:53:58.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,他曾提出 如果有探测器能够发射 他的一部分骨灰\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} He had asked if a mission ever did get launched some of his ashes
Dialogue: 0,0:53:58.75,0:54:01.23,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,可以一同踏上旅程\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} could be sent on the journey.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:01.23,0:54:06.27,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,想想看 克莱德的骨灰飞过了冥王星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} And to think that Clyde's ashes, you know, flew by Pluto,
Dialogue: 0,0:54:06.27,0:54:09.51,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,他终于拜访了自己发现的\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and, you know, he was finally visiting the place
Dialogue: 0,0:54:09.51,0:54:12.03,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,那个星球 这真是太酷了\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} that he discovered, that was pretty cool.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:22.19,0:54:26.35,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我想说 冥王星在很多方面都令人震惊 让人大开眼界\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Now, I mean, Pluto was a shock and a revelation in so many ways.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:26.35,0:54:28.51,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我们简直都惊呆了\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Our jaws just dropped to the floor.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:30.15,0:54:34.15,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我们若没有发射前往那里的探测器\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} This amazing world that we would never have known about,
Dialogue: 0,0:54:34.15,0:54:36.23,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我们永远无法了解这个不可思议的世界\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} unless we sent a spacecraft out there.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:35.86,0:54:40.50,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,赖特山 可能为冰火山 高4千米
Dialogue: 0,0:54:40.50,0:54:44.02,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,刀状地貌 塔尔塔洛斯山脊地区
Dialogue: 0,0:54:48.15,0:54:51.55,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,飞越冥王星后 “新视野”号并没有停下脚步\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} But New Horizons didn't stop after its flyby of Pluto.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:54.83,0:54:57.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它还要再飞三年\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} It continued on for three more years,
Dialogue: 0,0:54:57.39,0:54:59.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,深入探索柯伊伯带\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ever deeper into the Kuiper belt.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:01.35,0:55:03.59,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,那里的温度几乎达到了绝对零度\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} The temperatures out there are almost absolute zero,
Dialogue: 0,0:55:03.59,0:55:06.35,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,所以一切都保存完好\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} so everything is so well preserved.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:07.87,0:55:10.47,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,柯伊伯带彻底改变了一切\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} The Kuiper belt completely changed everything.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:10.47,0:55:14.43,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,可以说它就像一个考古发掘现场 让我们可以了解\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} It's an archaeological dig, if you will, into the early history
Dialogue: 0,0:55:14.43,0:55:17.19,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,太阳系的早期历史 它就是科学世界里的一个仙境\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} of our solar system, so it's a scientific wonderland.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:19.55,0:55:21.43,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,2019年新年这一天\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} On New Year's Day, 2019,
Dialogue: 0,0:55:21.43,0:55:25.47,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,“新视野”号达到了柯伊伯带中心\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} New Horizons had reached the centre of the region...
Dialogue: 0,0:55:27.99,0:55:32.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,它即将邂逅人类迄今探测过的最遥远的天体\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ..and was about to encounter the most distant object ever visited.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:35.51,0:55:41.45,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,小行星天涯海角
Dialogue: 0,0:55:41.45,0:55:45.63,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,小行星天涯海角\N（长31公里）
Dialogue: 0,0:55:48.39,0:55:51.35,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,这可能是人类探测器\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} This object may be the most primitive object
Dialogue: 0,0:55:51.35,0:55:53.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,遇到过的最原始的天体\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} ever encountered by a spacecraft.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:54.71,0:55:59.47,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,看着现在的天涯海角 我们相当于回到了\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} By looking at Ultima Thule today, we think we're looking back in time
Dialogue: 0,0:55:59.47,0:56:01.59,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,太阳系起源的时期\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} to the origin of the solar system.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:02.71,0:56:07.31,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,46亿年前
Dialogue: 0,0:56:13.91,0:56:18.79,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,天涯海角也许就诞生于无数次天体撞击中的一次\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Ultima Thule's formation was perhaps just one of the countless collisions
Dialogue: 0,0:56:18.79,0:56:20.91,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,正是这些撞击形成了各个行星\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} that formed the planets themselves.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:27.47,0:56:31.51,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,但它不知怎么逃脱出来 被扔进了\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} But, somehow, it escaped and was flung far out
Dialogue: 0,0:56:31.51,0:56:33.03,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,遥远的柯伊伯带\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} into the Kuiper belt.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:34.35,0:56:37.43,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,在距离太阳数十亿公里的地方\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} The worlds out there, which are billions of miles
Dialogue: 0,0:56:37.43,0:56:42.87,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,那些天体隐藏了太多的谜团\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} from the Sun, there are so many mysteries kept in these objects,
Dialogue: 0,0:56:40.02,0:56:43.82,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,诺亚·啥蒙德博士 行星科学家
Dialogue: 0,0:56:42.87,0:56:45.75,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我们能够真的走出去 去探索它们\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and we can really go out and explore them, and start
Dialogue: 0,0:56:45.75,0:56:47.91,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,去解开这些谜团\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} to understand these mysteries.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:49.79,0:56:53.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,与在它之前的每一次探测任务一样 “新视野”号帮助我们\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} Like every mission before it, New Horizons has helped write
Dialogue: 0,0:56:53.71,0:56:55.27,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,书写出关于这些行星的故事\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} the story of the planets.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:00.51,0:57:03.71,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,而这个故事的讲述才刚刚开始\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} A story that we're only just beginning to tell.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:06.70,0:57:11.66,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,利·弗莱彻博士 莱斯特大学
Dialogue: 0,0:57:06.79,0:57:09.91,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,太阳系的那些行星就在我们的后院\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} The planets of our solar system, they're in our back yard.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:10.03,0:57:12.55,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我们拥有的技术使我们得以走出去\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} We have the technology to be able to go
Dialogue: 0,0:57:12.55,0:57:14.55,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,并踏足行星表面\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and stand on these surfaces.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:16.39,0:57:19.83,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我希望能够到太空去 能够继续这项\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} To be able to go out there and be able to continue doing
Dialogue: 0,0:57:17.42,0:57:23.26,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,埃德加·里韦拉-瓦伦丁博士 月球与行星研究所
Dialogue: 0,0:57:19.83,0:57:22.67,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,关于人类自然本质的事业\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} something that is very natural and intrinsic to all of us,
Dialogue: 0,0:57:22.67,0:57:26.39,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我想解答一些重大的问题 去探索未知世界\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} and that is answering the big questions and exploring the unknown.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:31.51,0:57:33.95,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,我觉得我们对行星的探索绝对只是\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} I feel as though we're absolutely just at the beginning
Dialogue: 0,0:57:33.95,0:57:36.35,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,刚开了一个头\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} of planetary exploration.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:36.35,0:57:39.43,方正黑体_GBK-16-白字,NTP,0,0,0,,还有很多探索工作等着我们去完成\N{{\fntahoma\fs11\1c&H0080FF&\fnSitka Small\i1} There's a lot of exploration left for us.


